ical, and politics become funny. A series of original essays focus on a range of programs, from The Daily Show to South Park, Da Ali G Show to The Colbert Report, The Boondocks to Saturday Night Live, Lil' Bush to Chappelle's Show, along with Internet D.I.Y. satire and essays on British and Canadian satire. They all offer insights into what today's class of satire tells us about the current state of politics, of television, of citizenship, all the while suggesting what satire adds to the political realm that news and documentaries cannot.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aPolitical satire, American. 0aTelevision and politicszUnited States. 0aTelevision in politicszUnited States. 0aTelevision talk showszUnited States. 4aWhat. 4aabout. 4acitizenship. 4aclass. 4acomedy. 4acurrent. 4adoes. 4apolitics. 4asatire. 4astate. 4atelevision. 4atell. 4atodays. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aGray, Jonathan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJones, Jeffrey P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aThompson, Ethan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814733097423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814733097.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK